§aa-ln the same way, quia and quod, though not strictly resolvable by ut, both contain in themselves the force of the English ‘ that,' and are followed by a subjunctive. Quod, in the sense of ‘because,' is not necessarily followed by a subjunctive ; but in many cases this force seems to obtain where it is so used, because a causal may still be necessary to the sense of the whole proposition. Thus, after verbs of praising, blaming, or accusing, the relative and subjunctive follow more particularly, inasmuch as they contain in themselves the terms of the commendation or charge, not the reason assigned by the writer.
